  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards and recommendations for preventing money laundering.\n\n2. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime provides guidelines for combating money laundering internationally.\n\n3. Many countries have signed the Palermo Convention, which requires nations to criminalize money laundering.\n\n4. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering.\n\n5. Individual countries have their own specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and the Money Laundering Regulations in the United Kingdom.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nWhile enforcement varies, there are significant international efforts to prevent and prosecute money laundering.",
